{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584675"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:53:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:53:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14769"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14769"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.73,0.02,0.13,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66233"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7460"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14769"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51681"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5049"},{"type":"tags","id":"5321"},{"type":"tags","id":"11061"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18265"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22145"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66233"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman at 36 weeks gestation presents to the Emergency Department with severe headache and confusion. Her blood pressure is 165/100 mmHg with hyper-reflexia and 3+ proteinuria on urinalysis. She has no known medical conditions and has had a low risk uncomplicated pregnancy. She proceeds to experience a 30-second generalised tonic-clonic seizure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most appropriate as first-line drug therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Labetalol","Magnesium sulphate","Hydralazine","Diazepam","Midazolam"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with eclampsia (pre-eclampsia complicated by seizures). \u003Cstrong\u003EMagnesium sulphate\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line medication for both prevention and treatment of eclamptic seizures. It acts through multiple mechanisms including central nervous system depression, neuromuscular junction blockade, and cerebral vasodilation. Close monitoring is required during administration, specifically watching for loss of deep tendon reflexes (indicating toxicity), respiratory depression, and adequate urine output.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe alternative options are less appropriate:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELabetalol\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for blood pressure control in pre-eclampsia but does not prevent seizures\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydralazine\u003C/strong\u003E is an antihypertensive that may be used for acute blood pressure control but has no anti-seizure properties\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EMidazolam\u003C/strong\u003E are effective anticonvulsants but are not preferred as first-line agents due to their sedating effects on both mother and fetus. Eclamptic seizures are generally short and self limiting and often not \u0026gt;5 minutes. Benzodiazepines may be considered as second line agents or when there are prolonged seizures in pregnancy due to other causes such as epilepsy. It is important to note that if benzodiazepines are used that an experienced airway practitioner should be present as a pregnant patient with pre-eclampsia is likely to have a difficult to manage airway. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile blood pressure control is important in pre-eclampsia/eclampsia, preventing further seizures takes priority in this scenario. Multiple studies have shown magnesium sulphate to be superior to other anticonvulsants for preventing eclamptic seizures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Magnesium sulphate is the first-line medication for management of eclamptic seizures","Magnesium sulphate acts as a central nervous system depressant and vasodilator.","Clinical monitoring during magnesium therapy includes deep tendon reflexes, respiratory rate, and urine output."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Society of Obstetric Medicine of Australia and New Zealand (SOMANZ). Hypertension in Pregnancy Guideline 2023 [Internet]. Updated 2023 Jun 30. Available from: https://www.somanz.org/content/uploads/2023/06/SOMANZ_Hypertension_in_Pregnancy_Guideline_2023_Updated_30.6.23.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51681"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14769"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51681"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T15:34:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T16:21:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{